[13:13] <lucs> I'm amazed that all these covenants and other codes of conduct are popping up all over the place.

[13:14] <lucs> It looks like at least a whole generation forgot or was not taught or ignores a simple concept:

[13:14] <lucs> Behave

[13:14] <sjn> masak: First impression; it's not horribly bad; maybe little is said about how the document evolves, and it leaves terms like "appropriate", "fair", "offensive" and "inappropriate" to be defined by the project maintainers... :-\

[13:15] <masak> lucs: I've come to think that "behave" isn't enough and that an explicit Code of Conduct can be better than none

[13:15] <masak> sjn: well, take something like the Perl 5 IRC ecosystem

[13:15] <lucs> masak: Yes, people appear not to know what behave means.

[13:15] <masak> lucs: I don't think it's because we've left some lovely Golden Age, though

[13:16] <masak> lucs: I think this is what happens when communities grow and mature

[13:16] <jast> personally, the only reason I'm not put off by the language in Codes of Conduct is that I don't read them and rely on my common sense being enough

[13:16] <masak> sjn: people like mst perform a community service by intervening when someone acts in a trolling way, kicking and banning as needed

[13:17] <DrEeevil> I find them very confusing

[13:17] <masak> sjn: it's a job I don't imagine is very fulfilling, but it's needed

[13:17] <DrEeevil> most are badly worded and arbitrary, which makes enforcement very ugly

[13:17] <sjn> yeah

[13:17] <jast> my point is that you can just as easily intervene when there is no code of conduct

[13:17] <masak> sjn: I get the impression that "mst and his clique" end up getting a lot of hate/flames because of it

[13:17] <masak> sjn: but I'd rather they keep cleaning up obvious trolls than not

[13:18] <masak> (and rather them than me, too) :/

[13:18] <sjn> To me the text looks like the type of ad-hoc "legal" document that might curb certain behaviour, but at the cost of taking away attention from just helping eachother with the everyday community work

[13:18] <masak> jast: sure, of course

[13:18] <jast> at the core is this: put up a document of rules and you end up getting a legal system developed around it, whether you want one or not

[13:19] <masak> Perl 6's one venture into the code-of-conduct thing was a document that can be summarized as "just be level-headed and reasonable, OK? give people the benefit of the doubt and don't yell"

[13:19] <jast> that sounds reasonable ;)

[13:19] <masak> well

[13:19] <sjn> masak: I like the Reasonable Person Principle

[13:20] <masak> then the author of that document went and had a big argument with someone on the channel

[13:20] <masak> and wouldn't calm down or listen to arguments

[13:20] <DrEeevil> jast: you might end up with an acute infection of bureaucrats ;)

[13:20] <masak> and ended up leaving the community

[13:21] <masak> not sure a different code-of-conduct could've prevented that, but...

[13:21] <sjn> http://www.irc.perl.org/reasonable_person.html

[13:21] <jast> definitely not

[13:21] <masak> ...it made me conclude that "just be reasonable" isn't always enough

[13:21] <jast> that seems to me like inverse logic

[13:22] <jast> "the document did not prevent the behaviour it was meant to highlight as being bad, therefore it's not sufficient"

[13:22] <jast> if that's your standard, no document will achieve it

[13:22] <masak> more like "the author of the document couldn't live up to the guideline outlined in the document"

[13:23] <jast> that's a failure of the author, not of the document

[13:23] <masak> more the former than the latter, yes

[13:23] <masak> anyway, I see what you're saying

[13:23] <masak> I'm still thinking about all these things

[13:24] <masak> still not convinced either way

